{"title_page": "Girish and The Chronicles", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{COI|date=April 2019}}\n{{advert|date=May 2018}}\n{{refimprove|date=May 2018}}\n}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Girish And The Chronicles(GATC)\n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = pk\n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| background       = group_or_band\n| alias            = GATC\n| class            = \"wikitable\"\n| origin           = [[Gangtok]], [[Sikkim]], [[India]]\n| based out of     = [[Bangalore]], [[Karnataka]], [[India]]\n| genre            = [[Hard rock]], [[Heavy Metal music|heavy metal]], [[Melodic Rock]]\n| years_active     = 2009\u2013present\n| label            = [[Universal Music India]], Lions Pride Music (Denmark)\n| Album(s)         = [[Back on Earth (2014)]]\n[[Rock The Highway (2020)]]\n| Single(s)        = [[Endless Road (2017)]], [[Walking the Line (2018)]], [[Rock the Highway (2018)]]\n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = https://www.girishandthechronicles.com\n| current_members  = * Girish Pradhan\n* Suraz Karki\n* Yogesh Pradhan\n* Nagen Mongranti\n* Krishh Datta\n| past_members     = *Mishael Jiwandan Pradhan\n* Annutri Kaushik\n* Noel Lepcha<ref>http://indianbandshub.blogspot.com/2010/09/girish-and-chronicles.html?m=1</ref><ref name=\"Scribido\">http://scribidomagazine.com/girish-and-the-chronicles-unplugged/</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Girish and The Chronicles''' (commonly abbreviated as '''GATC''') is an [[India]]n [[Hard rock]]/[[Heavy metal music|Melodic Rock/Heavy Metal]] band from [[Gangtok]], [[Sikkim]], formed in 2009, by [[Vocalist]] Girish Pradhan. They have been based out of [[Bengaluru]], [[Karnataka]], since 2013, after their return from Hong Kong (2012 - 2013).<ref name=\"metalassault.com\">http://metalassault.com/Interviews/2013/02/07/a-detailed-conversation-with-vocalist-extraordinaire-girish-pradhan/</ref><ref>http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news-and-interviews/Musical-journey-of-Girish-Pradhan/articleshow/10115401.cms</ref>  \n\n==History==\nThe line up started in 2006 with Guitarist Suraz Karki and Girish Pradhan. Nagen Sarki, a drummer who was working with the band Still Waters, joined the line-up, on Suraz\u2019s recommendation. The guitarist\u2019s long time friend Vishal Pradhan also joined the band as the bass player.\n\nPrior to this, Girish was a part of a band named Anarchy, from Gangtok, of which his brother Yogesh Pradhan was the drummer. He later became the bassist and producer of GATC.  Suraz, Nagen and Vishal collectively were also a part of a band named Mukti, in the district of [[Namchi]], in Sikkim. The new group formed decided to keep the name Mukti. They started playing small gigs in Gangtok and [[Darjeeling]]. \n\nFrom 2007 to 2009, the line up was broken. In April 2008, Girish temporarily moved back to Gangtok and reunited with Suraz to form a line up to take part in a local band competition. The group was named \u201cRevolving Barrel\u201d, with drummer Ronald Pradhan and bassist Noel Lepcha. \n\nThe later half of 2008 saw Pradhan travel to Nepal, Kathmandu. Ronald had moved to the city and suggested that they reform Revolving Barrel there. Joined by bassist Lokesh Thapa (Gingerfeet/Still waters) and an old time friend of Ronald, Jatin Pradhan on the guitars, Revolving Barrel was now based out of Kathmandu. Back in Gangtok, Suraz and Nagen joined/formed \u201cA.live!\u201d.  A.Live went on to win the Mangan Rock Fest in the district of Mangan, Sikkim, and the line up of Revolving Barrel came to an end. \n\nGirish returned to Gangtok in the later half of 2009 where Yogesh had come too. As the two brothers met, Yogesh suggested that they record a single original. His YouTube channel, then named \u201cGirish Pradhan\u201d, could be used as a platform to promote it.  They started working on a song which Girish had been working on during his stay in Nepal. It was named, \u201dAngel\u201d. It was completed in autumn 2009 and was first released by the magazine T.N.T ([[The North East Times|The Northeast Times]]) in their seasonal CD release, Great Eastern Rock Volume II<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.assamtimes.org/node/3466|title=TNT- Great eastern Rock volume 2 Cd features 17 bands from the Northeast|date=2010-01-05|website=Assam Times|language=en|access-date=2019-05-31}}</ref>. The brothers started performing acoustic sets in Cafe Live and Loud. However, Yogesh had to leave to complete his course. Girish started doing solo unplugged sessions in the pub. Soon, Noel and Nagen, who no longer worked with \u201cA.live!\u201d, joined on bass and drums. Girish took up the role of a vocalist and a lead guitarist. The YouTube channel, the solo single, \u201cAngel\u201d and Cafe Live and Loud had turned the singer\u2019s name into a small brand of its own. The line-up was finally named Girish and The Chronicles, with Yogesh acting as the producer for the band. The band had weekly performances at Cafe Live and Loud and did a debut open concert with the spastic society on Friday the 13 October 2009, sharing the stage with [[Lou Majaw]].\n\nThe band was invited to participate in various competitions and went on to headline small college fests. The first competition they took part in was Alcheringa, Rock o Phoenix, annually held at IIT Guwahati. They were temporarily joined by violinist/keyboardist Mischael Jiwandan Pradhan, a college mate of Girish. Soon in the weeks that followed, participating in such competitions because a regular routine for the band from January till April. Parts of Assam, West Bengal and other parts of the country were covered. In April, the band won auditions to a music awards festival named \u201c[[Sun\u010dane Skale|Suncane Skale]]\u201d, to be held in [[Montenegro]]. The band recorded an original single which was to be complied in the festival\u2019s CD release. The tracks were sent to Yogesh for drums/keyboards and arrangement. The lyrics was written in collaboration with an old friend of Girish, Mausami Khushbu Rai. The song was named \u201cAngel\u2019s Angel\u201d and later changed to \u201cYesteryears\u201d.  They travelled to Montenegro, where the band was awarded first runners up to the title of \u201cSummer song\u201d. The song was played in European radio. On returning to Delhi, the band was covered by various TV channels such as Aaj Tak and CNN IBN along with printed media like The Telegraph<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/states/west-bengal/suncane-invite-for-sikkim-band-girish-n-the-chronicles-off-to-rock-europe/cid/506719|title=Suncane invite for Sikkim band - Girish 'N' The Chronicles off to rock europe|website=www.telegraphindia.com|language=en|access-date=2019-05-09}}</ref>. They were also invited to the Sikkim Governor\u2019s office and The Chief Minister\u2019s office of Sikkim for receiving congratulations. Later the same year, the band was empaneled in the [[Indian Council for Cultural Relations]] ([[ICCR]]). \n\nIn 2011, the band was invited for a performance at the [[The Heritage Academy, Kolkata|Heritage academ]]<nowiki/>y, Kolkata when Noel decided to leave the band. They called Yogesh, who was originally a drummer-turned-guitarist to fill in for the bass. While the YouTube channel was doing a good job of marketing the band, it was around September when an event organising company Ojone - O3 events led by entrepreneur Ujjwal Mukhia, invited the band to perform at the Hard Rock Cafe Bangalore.  The band did a series of small shows around the city. During this time an earthquake struck Sikkim. The band still in Bengaluru, worried for their families, came up with the song \u201c''A New Beginning''\u201d. In two days, the song was recorded at Sound Glitz Studio, and released. Girish also participated in the Yamaha Asian Beat national Finals with his other project Silver Tears during this time, where he won the best vocalist award.<ref>https://www.deccanherald.com/amp/content/187255/metal-singer-girish-pradhan-wins.htm</ref> The band got a chance to participate in the finals of the same competition on an international level, held at [[Seoul]], [[South Korea]].<ref>https://id.yamaha.com/id/news_events/contents/asianbeat/history/2011/index.htm</ref> At around the same time, Girish was offered a contract in the clubs of Hong Kong as a vocalist. Back in Gangtok, it was decided that the band would take in Abhishek Lemo Gurung (Still Waters/Gingerfeet) as their temporary vocalist. They decided to take part in the ''[[Hornbill Festival]]''  held at ''[[Nagaland]],'' where they were runners up, with Suraz named best guitarist and Abhishek best vocalist. In their return to Gangtok, they formed a blues trio and were performing regular gigs in the town.\n\n2012 saw the frontman of the band spending a few months in various clubs of Hong Kong as a singer. One club in particular was named ''Escape'', located in the streets of Wanchai . After a few months of working. He successfully made a deal with the club owners for bringing GATC to Hong Kong for a small tour and then join the clubs under contract for a year. After a year long stay the band finally decided on going back home and compile an album.  \n\nAfter returning to India, Pradhan started with a solo performance at the Punjab Engineering College Fest. In early 2013, the band stayed in Gangtok for three months (January-March), where the album was completed. It was backed up by the editor of TNT magazine Pradyot Manikya. Although the album was complete, the band wanted to re-record everything replacing the Fender Stratocaster guitar takes with Gibson Les Pauls. Angel was re-recorded wholly along with the other songs. The band reconnected with Ojone and decided to relocate to Bengaluru, Karnataka. They started off by co-headlining BMS college fest along with Lagori and [[Kryptos (band)|Kryptos]]. Soon with Ujjwal Mukhia as their new manager, the band took an independent house in the city where they started finishing off the album. The band got a chance to open for [[Hoobastank]], who were to perform<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rollingstoneindia.com/hoobastank-to-perform-in-shillong/|title=Hoobastank To Perform In Shillong -|date=2013-06-08|website=My Site|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-09}}</ref> in Shillong, Meghalaya. It was organised by TNT magazine. GATC started performing frequently in the Bengaluru city\u2019s prominent venues such as Take 5, B-Flat, Hard Rock Cafe and Vapour.  \n\nGATC released their first album - 'Back On Earth\u2019 consisting of 14 Tracks in August, 2014 under [[Universal Music Group]] label. The album release was followed by a national Hard Rock Cafe Tour. The album was promoted by Contrabands, which was a property of [[Universal Music Group]], [[VH1]] & [[Hard Rock Cafe]]. Angel was chosen for featuring on VH1.    \n\n2018    \n\nGATC did an intensive North-East India tour during the months of November and December covering regions of Meghalaya, Sikkim, Manipur, Mizoram and Assam.     \n\nThe band ended the year by releasing their single, \u201c''Rock the Highway''\u201d, on YouTube and other online platforms, worldwide. The song gained a good response from many parts of the world. It was also featured by [[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock Magazine]] in their \u201cTracks of the week<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loudersound.com/features/tracks-of-the-week-new-music-and-videos-from-the-raconteurs-paul-mccartney-and-more|title=Tracks Of The Week: new music and videos from The Raconteurs, Paul McCartney and more|last=Rock|first=Polly Glass2019-01-02T14:49:21Z Classic|website=Classic Rock Magazine|language=en|access-date=2019-05-31}}</ref>\u201d, section. Soon after, it was featured in the rock magazine Sleaze Roxx <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sleazeroxx.com/girish-and-the-chronicles-release-video-for-rock-the-highway/|title=Girish and The Chronicles release video for \u201cRock The Highway\u201d \u2013 Sleaze Roxx|last=Olivier|language=en-CA|access-date=2019-05-31}}</ref>.      \n\n2019 Started off with the band associating with the renowned guitarist [[Baiju Dharmajan]]. They performed at the annual Sikkim Tourism Red Panda festival together and then headed off to Bengaluru to open for [[Tesseract (band)|TesseracT]] at [[Indian Institute of Science]]. The team was then invited for North-East festival, held at [[CentralWorld|Central World]], [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]]. They performed for two consecutive nights. Coming back to Bengaluru, they started writing new material for their second album, which has already started with the release of \u201c''Rock The Highway''\u201d.    \n\nThe band signed up with Lion\u2019s Pride Music<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.melodicrock.it/2019/05/gatc-girish-and-the-chronicles-nuova-band-dallindia-nel-roster-di-lions-pride-music/|title=GATC (Girish And The Chronicles): nuova band dall'India nel roster di Lions Pride Music {{!}} MelodicRock.it|website=www.melodicrock.it|language=it-IT|access-date=2019-05-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://heavyparadise.blogspot.com/2019/05/lions-pride-music-new-signing-girish.html|title=HEAVY PARADISE, THE PARADISE OF MELODIC ROCK!: Lions Pride Music new signing Girish And The Chronicles (GATC)|last=Paradise|first=Heavy|date=2019-05-24|website=HEAVY PARADISE, THE PARADISE OF MELODIC ROCK!|access-date=2019-05-26}}</ref>, a [[Denmark]] based record label on the 22nd of May, 2019, for their upcoming album by the name \u201cRock The Highway\u201d, which is scheduled to release world-wide, in April 2020.  \n\n== Members ==\nMembers of GATC.<ref>[http://www.telegraphindia.com/1120428/jsp/siliguri/story_15427895.jsp#.UWfTEV18uo8 The Telegraph]</ref>\n* Girish Pradhan \u2013 Vocals/Guitars\n* Suraz Karki \u2013 Lead guitars\n* Yogesh Pradhan \u2013 Bass guitars\n* Nagen Mongranti \u2013 Drums\n* Krishh Datta \u2013 Keyboard\n\n== Songs ==\n* Angel (2009)<ref name=\"Scribido\" /><ref>http://www.thaindian.com/newsportal/entertainment/indian-band-girish-n-the-chronicles-at-suncane-skale-music-competition_100391912.html</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.zomato.com/events/bangalore/girish-and-the-chronicles-100001507 |title=Archived copy |access-date=22 April 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130920035647/http://www.zomato.com/events/bangalore/girish-and-the-chronicles-100001507 |archive-date=20 September 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-09-26/news-and-interviews/30201095_1_musical-journey-music-school-gnc</ref>\n* A New Beginning (2011)<ref>http://isikkim.com/a-new-beginning-a-song-by-girish-the-chronicles-to-sep-18-quake-victims/</ref>\n* Golden Crown (2009)\n* Ride To Hell (2014)\n* Smile Little Child \n*Loaded \n*Revolving Barrel (2014)\n*Endless Road  (2016)\n*Rock the Highway (2018)\n*Born with a big Attitude (2014)\n*Yesteryears (2010)\n*Hey you (2014)\n*I wanna get that loving again \n\n\nSee also\n\n*[[Pin Drop Violence]]\n*[[Kryptos (band)]]\n*[[Bhayanak Maut]]\n*[[Nicotine (band)]]\n*[[Inner Sanctum (band)]]\n*[[Scribe (band)]]\n*[[Demonic Resurrection]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Twitter}}\n\n[[Category:Indian rock music groups]]\n[[Category:People from Gangtok]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2009]]\n[[Category:Musical quartets]]\n[[Category:Artists from Sikkim]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{COI|date=April 2019}}\n{{advert|date=May 2018}}\n{{refimprove|date=May 2018}}\n}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Girish And The Chronicles(GATC)\n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = pk\n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| background       = group_or_band\n| alias            = GATC\n| class            = \"wikitable\"\n| origin           = [[Gangtok]], [[Sikkim]], [[India]]\n| based out of     = [[Bangalore]], [[Karnataka]], [[India]]\n| genre            = [[Hard rock]], [[Heavy Metal music|heavy metal]], [[Melodic Rock]]\n| years_active     = 2009\u2013present\n| label            = [[Universal Music India]], Lions Pride Music (Denmark)\n| Album(s)         = [[Back on Earth (2014)]]\n[[Rock The Highway (2020)]]\n| Single(s)        = [[Endless Road (2017)]], [[Walking the Line (2018)]], [[Rock the Highway (2018)]]\n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = https//:www.girishandthechronicles.com\n| current_members  = * Girish Pradhan\n* Suraz Karki\n* Yogesh Pradhan\n* Nagen Mongranti\n* Krishh Datta\n| past_members     = *Mishael Jiwandan Pradhan\n* Annutri Kaushik\n* Noel Lepcha<ref>http://indianbandshub.blogspot.com/2010/09/girish-and-chronicles.html?m=1</ref><ref name=\"Scribido\">http://scribidomagazine.com/girish-and-the-chronicles-unplugged/</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Girish and The Chronicles''' (commonly abbreviated as '''GATC''') is an [[India]]n [[Hard rock]]/[[Heavy metal music|Melodic Rock/Heavy Metal]] band from [[Gangtok]], [[Sikkim]], formed in 2009, by [[Vocalist]] Girish Pradhan. They have been based out of [[Bengaluru]], [[Karnataka]], since 2013, after their return from Hong Kong (2012 - 2013).<ref name=\"metalassault.com\">http://metalassault.com/Interviews/2013/02/07/a-detailed-conversation-with-vocalist-extraordinaire-girish-pradhan/</ref><ref>http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news-and-interviews/Musical-journey-of-Girish-Pradhan/articleshow/10115401.cms</ref>  \n\n==History==\nThe line up started in 2006 with Guitarist Suraz Karki and Girish Pradhan. Nagen Sarki, a drummer who was working with the band Still Waters, joined the line-up, on Suraz\u2019s recommendation. The guitarist\u2019s long time friend Vishal Pradhan also joined the band as the bass player.\n\nPrior to this, Girish was a part of a band named Anarchy, from Gangtok, of which his brother Yogesh Pradhan was the drummer. He later became the bassist and producer of GATC.  Suraz, Nagen and Vishal collectively were also a part of a band named Mukti, in the district of [[Namchi]], in Sikkim. The new group formed decided to keep the name Mukti. They started playing small gigs in Gangtok and [[Darjeeling]]. \n\nFrom 2007 to 2009, the line up was broken. In April 2008, Girish temporarily moved back to Gangtok and reunited with Suraz to form a line up to take part in a local band competition. The group was named \u201cRevolving Barrel\u201d, with drummer Ronald Pradhan and bassist Noel Lepcha. \n\nThe later half of 2008 saw Pradhan travel to Nepal, Kathmandu. Ronald had moved to the city and suggested that they reform Revolving Barrel there. Joined by bassist Lokesh Thapa (Gingerfeet/Still waters) and an old time friend of Ronald, Jatin Pradhan on the guitars, Revolving Barrel was now based out of Kathmandu. Back in Gangtok, Suraz and Nagen joined/formed \u201cA.live!\u201d.  A.Live went on to win the Mangan Rock Fest in the district of Mangan, Sikkim, and the line up of Revolving Barrel came to an end. \n\nGirish returned to Gangtok in the later half of 2009 where Yogesh had come too. As the two brothers met, Yogesh suggested that they record a single original. His YouTube channel, then named \u201cGirish Pradhan\u201d, could be used as a platform to promote it.  They started working on a song which Girish had been working on during his stay in Nepal. It was named, \u201dAngel\u201d. It was completed in autumn 2009 and was first released by the magazine T.N.T ([[The North East Times|The Northeast Times]]) in their seasonal CD release, Great Eastern Rock Volume II<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.assamtimes.org/node/3466|title=TNT- Great eastern Rock volume 2 Cd features 17 bands from the Northeast|date=2010-01-05|website=Assam Times|language=en|access-date=2019-05-31}}</ref>. The brothers started performing acoustic sets in Cafe Live and Loud. However, Yogesh had to leave to complete his course. Girish started doing solo unplugged sessions in the pub. Soon, Noel and Nagen, who no longer worked with \u201cA.live!\u201d, joined on bass and drums. Girish took up the role of a vocalist and a lead guitarist. The YouTube channel, the solo single, \u201cAngel\u201d and Cafe Live and Loud had turned the singer\u2019s name into a small brand of its own. The line-up was finally named Girish and The Chronicles, with Yogesh acting as the producer for the band. The band had weekly performances at Cafe Live and Loud and did a debut open concert with the spastic society on Friday the 13 October 2009, sharing the stage with [[Lou Majaw]].\n\nThe band was invited to participate in various competitions and went on to headline small college fests. The first competition they took part in was Alcheringa, Rock o Phoenix, annually held at IIT Guwahati. They were temporarily joined by violinist/keyboardist Mischael Jiwandan Pradhan, a college mate of Girish. Soon in the weeks that followed, participating in such competitions because a regular routine for the band from January till April. Parts of Assam, West Bengal and other parts of the country were covered. In April, the band won auditions to a music awards festival named \u201c[[Sun\u010dane Skale|Suncane Skale]]\u201d, to be held in [[Montenegro]]. The band recorded an original single which was to be complied in the festival\u2019s CD release. The tracks were sent to Yogesh for drums/keyboards and arrangement. The lyrics was written in collaboration with an old friend of Girish, Mausami Khushbu Rai. The song was named \u201cAngel\u2019s Angel\u201d and later changed to \u201cYesteryears\u201d.  They travelled to Montenegro, where the band was awarded first runners up to the title of \u201cSummer song\u201d. The song was played in European radio. On returning to Delhi, the band was covered by various TV channels such as Aaj Tak and CNN IBN along with printed media like The Telegraph<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/states/west-bengal/suncane-invite-for-sikkim-band-girish-n-the-chronicles-off-to-rock-europe/cid/506719|title=Suncane invite for Sikkim band - Girish 'N' The Chronicles off to rock europe|website=www.telegraphindia.com|language=en|access-date=2019-05-09}}</ref>. They were also invited to the Sikkim Governor\u2019s office and The Chief Minister\u2019s office of Sikkim for receiving congratulations. Later the same year, the band was empaneled in the [[Indian Council for Cultural Relations]] ([[ICCR]]). \n\nIn 2011, the band was invited for a performance at the [[The Heritage Academy, Kolkata|Heritage academ]]<nowiki/>y, Kolkata when Noel decided to leave the band. They called Yogesh, who was originally a drummer-turned-guitarist to fill in for the bass. While the YouTube channel was doing a good job of marketing the band, it was around September when an event organising company Ojone - O3 events led by entrepreneur Ujjwal Mukhia, invited the band to perform at the Hard Rock Cafe Bangalore.  The band did a series of small shows around the city. During this time an earthquake struck Sikkim. The band still in Bengaluru, worried for their families, came up with the song \u201c''A New Beginning''\u201d. In two days, the song was recorded at Sound Glitz Studio, and released. Girish also participated in the Yamaha Asian Beat national Finals with his other project Silver Tears during this time, where he won the best vocalist award.<ref>https://www.deccanherald.com/amp/content/187255/metal-singer-girish-pradhan-wins.htm</ref> The band got a chance to participate in the finals of the same competition on an international level, held at [[Seoul]], [[South Korea]].<ref>https://id.yamaha.com/id/news_events/contents/asianbeat/history/2011/index.htm</ref> At around the same time, Girish was offered a contract in the clubs of Hong Kong as a vocalist. Back in Gangtok, it was decided that the band would take in Abhishek Lemo Gurung (Still Waters/Gingerfeet) as their temporary vocalist. They decided to take part in the ''[[Hornbill Festival]]''  held at ''[[Nagaland]],'' where they were runners up, with Suraz named best guitarist and Abhishek best vocalist. In their return to Gangtok, they formed a blues trio and were performing regular gigs in the town.\n\n2012 saw the frontman of the band spending a few months in various clubs of Hong Kong as a singer. One club in particular was named ''Escape'', located in the streets of Wanchai . After a few months of working. He successfully made a deal with the club owners for bringing GATC to Hong Kong for a small tour and then join the clubs under contract for a year. After a year long stay the band finally decided on going back home and compile an album.  \n\nAfter returning to India, Pradhan started with a solo performance at the Punjab Engineering College Fest. In early 2013, the band stayed in Gangtok for three months (January-March), where the album was completed. It was backed up by the editor of TNT magazine Pradyot Manikya. Although the album was complete, the band wanted to re-record everything replacing the Fender Stratocaster guitar takes with Gibson Les Pauls. Angel was re-recorded wholly along with the other songs. The band reconnected with Ojone and decided to relocate to Bengaluru, Karnataka. They started off by co-headlining BMS college fest along with Lagori and [[Kryptos (band)|Kryptos]]. Soon with Ujjwal Mukhia as their new manager, the band took an independent house in the city where they started finishing off the album. The band got a chance to open for [[Hoobastank]], who were to perform<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rollingstoneindia.com/hoobastank-to-perform-in-shillong/|title=Hoobastank To Perform In Shillong -|date=2013-06-08|website=My Site|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-09}}</ref> in Shillong, Meghalaya. It was organised by TNT magazine. GATC started performing frequently in the Bengaluru city\u2019s prominent venues such as Take 5, B-Flat, Hard Rock Cafe and Vapour.  \n\nGATC released their first album - 'Back On Earth\u2019 consisting of 14 Tracks in August, 2014 under [[Universal Music Group]] label. The album release was followed by a national Hard Rock Cafe Tour. The album was promoted by Contrabands, which was a property of [[Universal Music Group]], [[VH1]] & [[Hard Rock Cafe]]. Angel was chosen for featuring on VH1.    \n\n2018    \n\nGATC did an intensive North-East India tour during the months of November and December covering regions of Meghalaya, Sikkim, Manipur, Mizoram and Assam.     \n\nThe band ended the year by releasing their single, \u201c''Rock the Highway''\u201d, on YouTube and other online platforms, worldwide. The song gained a good response from many parts of the world. It was also featured by [[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock Magazine]] in their \u201cTracks of the week<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loudersound.com/features/tracks-of-the-week-new-music-and-videos-from-the-raconteurs-paul-mccartney-and-more|title=Tracks Of The Week: new music and videos from The Raconteurs, Paul McCartney and more|last=Rock|first=Polly Glass2019-01-02T14:49:21Z Classic|website=Classic Rock Magazine|language=en|access-date=2019-05-31}}</ref>\u201d, section. Soon after, it was featured in the rock magazine Sleaze Roxx <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sleazeroxx.com/girish-and-the-chronicles-release-video-for-rock-the-highway/|title=Girish and The Chronicles release video for \u201cRock The Highway\u201d \u2013 Sleaze Roxx|last=Olivier|language=en-CA|access-date=2019-05-31}}</ref>.      \n\n2019 Started off with the band associating with the renowned guitarist [[Baiju Dharmajan]]. They performed at the annual Sikkim Tourism Red Panda festival together and then headed off to Bengaluru to open for [[Tesseract (band)|TesseracT]] at [[Indian Institute of Science]]. The team was then invited for North-East festival, held at [[CentralWorld|Central World]], [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]]. They performed for two consecutive nights. Coming back to Bengaluru, they started writing new material for their second album, which has already started with the release of \u201c''Rock The Highway''\u201d.    \n\nThe band signed up with Lion\u2019s Pride Music<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.melodicrock.it/2019/05/gatc-girish-and-the-chronicles-nuova-band-dallindia-nel-roster-di-lions-pride-music/|title=GATC (Girish And The Chronicles): nuova band dall'India nel roster di Lions Pride Music {{!}} MelodicRock.it|website=www.melodicrock.it|language=it-IT|access-date=2019-05-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://heavyparadise.blogspot.com/2019/05/lions-pride-music-new-signing-girish.html|title=HEAVY PARADISE, THE PARADISE OF MELODIC ROCK!: Lions Pride Music new signing Girish And The Chronicles (GATC)|last=Paradise|first=Heavy|date=2019-05-24|website=HEAVY PARADISE, THE PARADISE OF MELODIC ROCK!|access-date=2019-05-26}}</ref>, a [[Denmark]] based record label on the 22nd of May, 2019, for their upcoming album by the name \u201cRock The Highway\u201d, which is scheduled to release world-wide, in April 2020.  \n\n== Members ==\nMembers of GATC.<ref>[http://www.telegraphindia.com/1120428/jsp/siliguri/story_15427895.jsp#.UWfTEV18uo8 The Telegraph]</ref>\n* Girish Pradhan \u2013 Vocals/Guitars\n* Suraz Karki \u2013 Lead guitars\n* Yogesh Pradhan \u2013 Bass guitars\n* Nagen Mongranti \u2013 Drums\n* Krishh Datta \u2013 Keyboard\n\n== Songs ==\n* Angel (2009)<ref name=\"Scribido\" /><ref>http://www.thaindian.com/newsportal/entertainment/indian-band-girish-n-the-chronicles-at-suncane-skale-music-competition_100391912.html</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.zomato.com/events/bangalore/girish-and-the-chronicles-100001507 |title=Archived copy |access-date=22 April 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130920035647/http://www.zomato.com/events/bangalore/girish-and-the-chronicles-100001507 |archive-date=20 September 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-09-26/news-and-interviews/30201095_1_musical-journey-music-school-gnc</ref>\n* A New Beginning (2011)<ref>http://isikkim.com/a-new-beginning-a-song-by-girish-the-chronicles-to-sep-18-quake-victims/</ref>\n* Golden Crown (2009)\n* Ride To Hell (2014)\n* Smile Little Child \n*Loaded \n*Revolving Barrel (2014)\n*Endless Road  (2016)\n*Rock the Highway (2018)\n*Born with a big Attitude (2014)\n*Yesteryears (2010)\n*Hey you (2014)\n*I wanna get that loving again \n\n\nSee also\n\n*[[Pin Drop Violence]]\n*[[Kryptos (band)]]\n*[[Bhayanak Maut]]\n*[[Nicotine (band)]]\n*[[Inner Sanctum (band)]]\n*[[Scribe (band)]]\n*[[Demonic Resurrection]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Twitter}}\n\n[[Category:Indian rock music groups]]\n[[Category:People from Gangtok]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2009]]\n[[Category:Musical quartets]]\n[[Category:Artists from Sikkim]]\n", "name_user": "Girishpradhan999", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added website link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Girish_and_The_Chronicles"}
{"title_page": "Andrew Madley", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox football official\n| name = Andy Madley\n| fullname = Andrew Madley\n| image =<!-- Deleted image removed:  [[File:AndyMadley.jpg|thumbnail]] -->\n| caption = \n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1983|9|5|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Huddersfield]], [[Yorkshire]], England\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| otheroccupation = Teacher\n| years1              = 2008\u20132010\n| league1             = [[The Football League]]\n| role1               = [[Referee (association football)|Assistant Referee]]\n| years2              = 2009\u20132011\n| league2             = [[Football Conference|Conference]]\n| role2               = [[Referee (association football)|Referee]]\n| years3              = 2010\u201311<br>2019\u2013\n| league3             = [[Premier League]]\n| role3               = [[Referee (association football)|Assistant Referee]]\n| years4              = 2011\u2013\n| league4             = [[Football League]]<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Football League |url=http://www.football-league.co.uk/global/matchofficialslist.aspx |title=List of EFL Match Officials |date=9 June 2016|accessdate=22 November 2016}}</ref>\n| role4               = [[Referee (association football)|Referee]]\n}}\n'''Andrew Madley''' (born 5 September 1983) is an English [[association football|football]] [[Referee (association football)|referee]].\n\n==Career==\n\nAndrew Madley began his refereeing career on the local [[Wakefield]] leagues. He quickly advanced through the levels before becoming a Level 3A referee in 2008. This allowed him to act as an assistant referee on the three Football League divisions. The following year he was promoted to the Panel List which allowed him to referee in the Conference divisions. He then progressed further the following year by becoming a Select Group Assistant Referee, officiating on the Premier League. In 2011, he progressed to his current role, a National List Referee, officiating in the three Football League divisions. Andrew is the older brother of former Select Group Referee [[Robert Madley]].\n\nFor the start of the 2016/17 season, Andrew was included as a Select Group 2 referee which sees him primarily referee in the Championship. He took charge of a Premier League game for the first time on 31 March 2018, a 2-2 draw between Watford and Bournemouth.\n\nIn June 2019, Madley was promoted to the Select Group 1 Referees list which will see him Referee Primarily in the Premier League.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bankes and Madley promoted for new season |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/1241817 |website=Premier League |accessdate=14 June 2019 |date=12 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Matches==\n\nMadley refereed the Football League Two Play-Off Semi-Final between [[Cheltenham Town F.C.|Cheltenham Town]] and [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]] on 4 May 2013 which ended 0\u20131 (0\u20132 agg).<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=Daily Mail |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2319069/Cheltenham-v-Northampton--live-League-Two-play-offs.html|title=LEAGUE TWO PLAY-OFFS: Cheltenham v Northampton - as it happens from the Abbey Business Stadium |accessdate=22 November 2016 |date=5 May 2013 |first=Gerard |last=Brand}}</ref> He also refereed the [[FA Vase]] Final on 9 May 2015 between [[Glossop North End F.C.|Glossop North End]] and [[North Shields F.C.|North Shields]], which finished 1\u20132.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=The FA |url=http://www.thefa.com/news/competitions/fa-vase/2015/may/glossop-north-end-north-shields-report |title=North Shields come from behind to lift The FA Vase |first=Jamie |last=Bradbury| |date=9 May 2015 |accessdate=22 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nMadley refereed the [[Football League One]] Play-Off Final between [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] and [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] on 24 May 2015.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=English Football League |url=http://www.football-league.co.uk/news/article/2015/andy-madley-to-referee-sky-bet-league-1-play-off-final-2453523.aspx |title=Andy Madley to referee Sky Bet League 1 Play-Off Final |date=12 May 2015|accessdate=22 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 May 2019, Madley refereed the FA Trophy Final at Wembley Stadium between [[Leyton Orient F.C.|Leyton Orient]] and [[A.F.C. Fylde|AFC Fylde]] ending in a 0-1 win for AFC Fylde.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48314552|title=FA Trophy final: AFC Fylde 1\u20130 Leyton Orient|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|first=Rob |last=Stevens|date=19 May 2019|accessdate=31 December 2019}}</ref> He also refereed the [[EFL League One]] Play Off Final between [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] and [[Sunderland F.C.|Sunderland]] on 26 May 2019, which Charlton won 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48324840|title=League One play-off final: Charlton Athletic 2\u20131 Sunderland|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|first=James |last=Law |date=26 May 2019|accessdate=31 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Premier League referees}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Madley, Andrew}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English football referees]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Huddersfield]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox football official\n| name = Andy Madley\n| fullname = Andrew Madley\n| image =<!-- Deleted image removed:  [[File:AndyMadley.jpg|thumbnail]] -->\n| caption = \n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1983|9|5|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Huddersfield]] |[[yorkshire]], England\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| otheroccupation = Teacher\n| years1              = 2008\u20132010\n| league1             = [[The Football League]]\n| role1               = [[Referee (association football)|Assistant Referee]]\n| years2              = 2009\u20132011\n| league2             = [[Football Conference|Conference]]\n| role2               = [[Referee (association football)|Referee]]\n| years3              = 2010\u201311<br>2019\u2013\n| league3             = [[Premier League]]\n| role3               = [[Referee (association football)|Assistant Referee]]\n| years4              = 2011\u2013\n| league4             = [[Football League]]<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Football League |url=http://www.football-league.co.uk/global/matchofficialslist.aspx |title=List of EFL Match Officials |date=9 June 2016|accessdate=22 November 2016}}</ref>\n| role4               = [[Referee (association football)|Referee]]\n}}\n'''Andrew Madley''' (born 5 September 1983) is an English [[association football|football]] [[Referee (association football)|referee]].\n\n==Career==\n\nAndrew Madley began his refereeing career on the local [[Wakefield]] leagues. He quickly advanced through the levels before becoming a Level 3A referee in 2008. This allowed him to act as an assistant referee on the three Football League divisions. The following year he was promoted to the Panel List which allowed him to referee in the Conference divisions. He then progressed further the following year by becoming a Select Group Assistant Referee, officiating on the Premier League. In 2011, he progressed to his current role, a National List Referee, officiating in the three Football League divisions. Andrew is the older brother of former Select Group Referee [[Robert Madley]].\n\nFor the start of the 2016/17 season, Andrew was included as a Select Group 2 referee which sees him primarily referee in the Championship. He took charge of a Premier League game for the first time on 31 March 2018, a 2-2 draw between Watford and Bournemouth.\n\nIn June 2019, Madley was promoted to the Select Group 1 Referees list which will see him Referee Primarily in the Premier League.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bankes and Madley promoted for new season |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/1241817 |website=Premier League |accessdate=14 June 2019 |date=12 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Matches==\n\nMadley refereed the Football League Two Play-Off Semi-Final between [[Cheltenham Town F.C.|Cheltenham Town]] and [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]] on 4 May 2013 which ended 0\u20131 (0\u20132 agg).<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=Daily Mail |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2319069/Cheltenham-v-Northampton--live-League-Two-play-offs.html|title=LEAGUE TWO PLAY-OFFS: Cheltenham v Northampton - as it happens from the Abbey Business Stadium |accessdate=22 November 2016 |date=5 May 2013 |first=Gerard |last=Brand}}</ref> He also refereed the [[FA Vase]] Final on 9 May 2015 between [[Glossop North End F.C.|Glossop North End]] and [[North Shields F.C.|North Shields]], which finished 1\u20132.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=The FA |url=http://www.thefa.com/news/competitions/fa-vase/2015/may/glossop-north-end-north-shields-report |title=North Shields come from behind to lift The FA Vase |first=Jamie |last=Bradbury| |date=9 May 2015 |accessdate=22 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nMadley refereed the [[Football League One]] Play-Off Final between [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] and [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] on 24 May 2015.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=English Football League |url=http://www.football-league.co.uk/news/article/2015/andy-madley-to-referee-sky-bet-league-1-play-off-final-2453523.aspx |title=Andy Madley to referee Sky Bet League 1 Play-Off Final |date=12 May 2015|accessdate=22 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 May 2019, Madley refereed the FA Trophy Final at Wembley Stadium between [[Leyton Orient F.C.|Leyton Orient]] and [[A.F.C. Fylde|AFC Fylde]] ending in a 0-1 win for AFC Fylde.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48314552|title=FA Trophy final: AFC Fylde 1\u20130 Leyton Orient|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|first=Rob |last=Stevens|date=19 May 2019|accessdate=31 December 2019}}</ref> He also refereed the [[EFL League One]] Play Off Final between [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] and [[Sunderland F.C.|Sunderland]] on 26 May 2019, which Charlton won 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48324840|title=League One play-off final: Charlton Athletic 2\u20131 Sunderland|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|first=James |last=Law |date=26 May 2019|accessdate=31 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Premier League referees}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Madley, Andrew}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English football referees]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Huddersfield]]\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update infobox", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrew_Madley"}
{"title_page": "Luigi Ventura", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type             = archbishop\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name             = Luigi Ventura \n| honorific-suffix = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| title            = Apostolic Nuncio emeritus to France\n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| church           = \n| archdiocese      = \n| province         = \n| metropolis       = \n| diocese          = \n| see              = \n| elected          = \n| appointed        = 22 September 2009\n| term             = \n| term_start       = \n| quashed          = \n| term_end         = 17 December 2019\n| predecessor      = [[Fortunato Baldelli]]\n| opposed          = \n| successor        = \n| other_post       = Titular Archbishop of Equilium\n<!---------- Orders ---------->\n| ordination       = 14 June 1969\n| ordained_by      = \n| consecration     = 29 April 1995\n| consecrated_by   = [[Angelo Sodano]]\n| cardinal         = \n| rank             = \n<!---------- Personal details ---------->\n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1944|12|09|df=yes}}\n| birth_place      = [[Borgosatollo]], Italy\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| buried           = \n| nationality      = \n| religion         = [[Roman Catholic]]\n| residence        = \n| parents          = \n| spouse           = \n| children         = \n| occupation       = \n| profession       = \n| previous_post    = {{unbulleted list|Apostolic Nuncio to Burkina Faso, Ivory Coast, and Niger (1995\u201399)|Apostolic Nuncio to Chile (1999\u20132001)|Apostolic Nuncio to Canada (2001\u201305)}}\n| education        =\n| alma_mater       = \n| motto            = Unitatem Spiritus Servare\n| signature        = \n| signature_alt    = \n| coat_of_arms     = Coat of arms of Luigi Ventura.svg\n| coat_of_arms_alt = \n<!---------- Other ---------->\n| other            = \n}}\n{{infobox bishopstyles |\n    name=Luigi Ventura|\n    dipstyle=[[The Most Reverend]] |\n    offstyle=[[Your Excellency]] |\n    relstyle=[[Archbishop]] |\n    deathstyle= |\n    image=Coat of arms of Luigi Ventura.svg|\n    image_size =200px|}}\n'''Luigi Ventura''' (born 9 December 1944) is an Italian prelate of the Catholic Church who was apostolic nuncio to France from 2009 to 2018. He became a nuncio and archbishop in 1995 and served in several African countries, Chile, and Canada before being posted to Paris.\n\nBeginning in January 2019 he was under investigation by French authorities for sexual crimes. In July 2019, the Vatican lifted his diplomatic immunity to allow him to face criminal charges. He was allowed to relocate to Rome; Pope Francis accepted his resignation in December 2019. The investigation remains open.\n\n==Career==\nVentura was born on 9 December 1944 in [[Borgosatollo]], Italy. He was ordained a priest on 14 June 1969 for the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Brescia|Diocese of Brescia]]. To prepare for a diplomatic career he entered the [[Pontifical Ecclesiastical Academy]] in 1967.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Pontifical Ecclesiastical Academy]]|language =it|access-date = 18 December 2019 | title = Pontificia Accademia Ecclesiastica, Ex-alunni 1950 \u2013 1999 |url = https://www.vatican.va/roman_curia/pontifical_academies/acdeccles/documents/1950-1999.htm }}</ref>\n\nHe joined the diplomatic service of the [[Holy See]] in 1978. He earned a doctor of letters and holds a [[Licentiate (degree)|licentiate]] in [[canon law]]. His assignments from 1978 to 1984 were in [[Brazil]], [[Bolivia]] and the [[United Kingdom]]. He then worked in Rome with the Section for Relations with States at the [[Secretariat of State (Holy See)|Secretariat of State]] until 1995.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/accused-nuncio-to-france-resigns-post-25730 | publisher = Catholic News Agency | access-date = 18 December 2019 | date= 17 December 2019 | title= Accused nuncio to France resigns post | first = Hannah | last = Brockhaus}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March 1995, [[Pope John Paul II]] appointed him [[titular archbishop]] of Equilium and apostolic nuncio to the [[Ivory Coast]], [[Burkina Faso]] and [[Niger]].<ref>{{cite book | page= 397 |access-date = 18 December 2019 | url = https://www.vatican.va/archive/aas/documents/AAS-87-1995-ocr.pdf |title = Acta Apostolicae Sedis | date= 1995| volume = LXXXVII }}</ref> He was consecrated a bishop on 29 April 1995 by Cardinal [[Angelo Sodano]], Secretary of State.{{cn|date=December 2019}} He was made nuncio to [[Chile]] on 25 March 1999.<ref>{{cite book | page= 479 |access-date = 18 December 2019 | url = https://www.vatican.va/archive/aas/documents/AAS-91-1999-ocr.pdf |title = Acta Apostolicae Sedis | date= 1999 | volume = LXXXXI }}</ref>\n\nOn 22 June 2001, John Paul named him apostolic nuncio to [[Canada]].<ref>{{cite news |access-date = 29 May 2019 | archive-date= 27 May 2014 | archive-url = https://archive.is/20140527173152/http://www.nationalpost.com/opinion/columnists/story.html?id=729cfb88-30f8-4171-9ace-7a2cf60ffbf4 |work= National Post |title=The Vatican's man in Canada|url = http://www.nationalpost.com/opinion/columnists/story.html?id=729cfb88-30f8-4171-9ace-7a2cf60ffbf4| url-status =dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite press release | title = Rinunce e Nomine, 22.06.2001| date= 22 June 2001 | language =it|url = http://press.vatican.va/content/salastampa/it/bollettino/pubblico/2001/06/22/0359/01058.html | publisher = Holy See Press Office}}</ref>\n\n[[Pope Benedict XVI]] appointed him apostolic nuncio to [[France]] on 22 September 2009,<ref>{{cite press release | title = Rinunce e Nomine, 22.09.2009 | date= 22 September 2009 | language =it|url =  http://press.vatican.va/content/salastampa/it/bollettino/pubblico/2009/09/22/0575/01336.html | publisher = Holy See Press Office}}</ref> replacing [[Fortunato Baldelli]] who had been appointed as [[Apostolic Penitentiary|Major Penitentiary of the Apostolic Penitentiary]].\n\n== Criminal allegations ==\n\nIn January 2019 the French authorities opened an investigation into Ventura after a junior official at Paris City Hall accused him of [[molestation]]. Ventura has not made comment on the allegations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.i24news.tv/en/news/international/europe/1576594182-pope-francis-lifts-pontifical-secret-for-sex-abuse-cases|title=Pope Francis lifts 'pontifical secret' for sex abuse cases|last=|first=|date=2019-12-17|website=[[i24NEWS]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213214944/https://www.i24news.tv/en/news/international/europe/1576594182-pope-francis-lifts-pontifical-secret-for-sex-abuse-cases|archive-date=13 February 2020|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 February 2019, ''[[Le Monde]]'' reported that a young male employed by the office of the mayor of Paris had filed a complaint for [[sexual assault]] against Ventura and that authorities had launched a formal inquiry in January.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.lemonde.fr/societe/article/2019/02/15/l-ambassadeur-du-pape-en-france-vise-par-une-enquete_5423780_3224.html | work = Le Monde | language = fr | title= L\u2019\" ambassadeur \" du pape en France, Luigi Ventura, vis\u00e9 par une enqu\u00eate pour \" agressions sexuelles \" | access-date = 29 May 2019 | date= 15 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | work = La Croix | access-date = 29 May 2019 | url = https://www.la-croix.com/Religion/Catholicisme/France/Le-nonce-apostolique-France-vise-enquete-agressions-sexuelles-2019-02-15-1201002817 | language = fr | date = 15 February 2019 | first = Gauthier | last = Vaillant|title= Le nonce apostolique en France vis\u00e9 par une enqu\u00eate pour agressions sexuelles }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.lejdd.fr/Societe/Justice/sopucons-dagression-sexuelle-le-cas-ventura-met-le-vatican-dans-lembarras-3859358 | language = fr | work = Journal de Dimanche | access-date = 29 May 2019 | title = Soup\u00e7ons d'agression sexuelle : le cas Ventura met le Vatican dans l'embarras| first = St\u00e9phane | last = Joahny | date= 17 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | access-date = 29 May 2019 | publisher = CNN | url = https://edition.cnn.com/2019/02/15/europe/vatican-france-envoy-luigi-ventura-investigation-intl/index.html | date= 15 February 2019 | title = Vatican envoy to France under investigation for sexual assault | first = Saskya | last = Vandoorne}}</ref> The city employee, Mathieu de La Souch\u00e8re, and two other accusers using aliases, have asked French officials to ask the Vatican to waive Ventura's [[diplomatic immunity]].<ref>{{cite news |work= La Lib\u00e9ration | url = https://www.liberation.fr/france/2019/02/28/emmanuel-macron-levez-l-immunite-diplomatique-du-nonce-apostolique_1711998 | access-date = 29 May 2019 | title = Emmanuel Macron, levez l'immunit\u00e9 diplomatique du nonce apostolique! | language = fr | date = 28 February 2019}}</ref> French European Minister [[Nathalie Loiseau]] said she expects the Vatican to allow Ventura to be tried.<ref>{{cite news | access-date = 29 May 2019 | date= 1 March 2019 | url = http://m.en.rfi.fr/europe/20190301-france-urges-vatican-action-papal-envoy-sex-abuse-luigi-ventura | publisher = RFI | title = France calls on Vatican to take action against envoy after sex abuse charges}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 February a Canadian man, Christian Vachon, charged Ventura had touched him improperly in July 2008 when he was 32.<ref>{{cite news| work = Pr\u00e9sence| language = fr | access-date =  30 May 2019 | date=26 February 2019 | url =http://presence-info.ca/article/judiciaire/premiere-plainte-d-inconduite-sexuelle-au-canada-contre-l-ancien-nonce | title = Premi\u00e8re plainte d\u2019inconduite sexuelle au Canada contre l\u2019ancien nonce | first =Philippe |last= Vaillancourt}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | access-date = 29 May 2019 | url = https://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/french-nuncio-accused-of-sexual-misconduct-during-time-in-canada-38730 | agency = Catholic News Agency | date= 1 March 2019 | title = French nuncio accused of sexual misconduct during time in Canada}}</ref> Vachon said Ventura's successor as Nuncio to Canada, Archbishop [[Luigi Bonazzi]], called him the day he registered his complaint to discuss it.<ref>{{cite news | access-date = 29 May 2019 | work = Crux | url = https://cruxnow.com/church-in-the-americas/2019/02/28/vatican-embassy-confirms-complaint-of-sexual-misconduct-against-ex-nuncio/ | title = Vatican embassy confirms complaint of sexual misconduct against ex-nuncio | first = Philippe | last = Vaillancourt |agency= Catholic News Service | date= 28 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nVentura allowed himself to be questioned by French police in April. At his own request, Ventura met with his four accusers on 22\u201323 May and denied their charges. The accusers' attorneys were not allowed to ask him questions.<ref name=confront>{{cite news | access-date = 29 May 2019 | url = https://www.la-croix.com/Religion/Catholicisme/France/Confronte-accusateurs-nonce-apostolique-nie-toute-agression-sexuelle-2019-05-23-1201024070 | title = Confront\u00e9 \u00e0 ses accusateurs, le nonce apostolique nie toute agression sexuelle |date= 23 May 2019| work = La Croix | first = Cl\u00e9mence | last = Houdaille | language = fr}}</ref> On 8 July a Vatican spokesperson said the [[Holy See]] had informed French authorities a week earlier that it was waiving Ventura's diplomatic immunity. He called it \"an extraordinary gesture\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/holy-see-waves-diplomatic-immunity-for-accused-nuncio-to-france-22125/|date= 8 July 2019 | title=Holy See waives diplomatic immunity for accused nuncio to France|website=Catholic News Agency|access-date=8 July 2019}}</ref> ''Le Monde'' reported it was the first withdrawal of diplomatic immunity on the part of the Vatican in modern history.<ref>{{cite news | access-date = 18 December 2019 | date= 17 December 2019 | language = fr | url = https://www.lemonde.fr/societe/article/2019/12/17/le-pape-francois-leve-le-secret-pontifical-sur-les-abus-sexuels-au-sein-de-l-eglise_6023182_3224.html | title= Le pape Fran\u00e7ois l\u00e8ve le secret pontifical sur les abus sexuels au sein de l\u2019Eglise catholique | first= C\u00e9cile | last = Chambraud }}</ref>\n\nAs of 30 September 2019, Ventura was living at a residence for retired priests in Rome,<ref>{{cite news | url = https://international.la-croix.com/news/papal-nuncio-to-france-accused-of-sexual-assault-back-in-rome/10933 | title= Papal nuncio to France accused of sexual assault back in Rome | date= 30 September 2019 | access-date = 17 December 2019 |newspaper=[[La Croix International]]}}</ref> still subject to French investigators and prosecution.<ref>{{cite news | access-date = 18 December 2019 | date= 17 December 2019 | work = The Tablet | title= Pope accepts France ambassador resignation| first = Christopher | last = Lamb| url = https://www.thetablet.co.uk/news/12298/pope-accepts-france-ambassador-resignation }}</ref>\n\n==Resignation==\nPope Francis accepted his resignation on 17 December 2019,<ref>{{cite press release | title = Resignations and Appointments, 17.12.2019  | date= 17 December 2019 | url = https://press.vatican.va/content/salastampa/en/bollettino/pubblico/2019/12/17/191217c.html  | publisher = Holy See Press Office}}</ref> which Ventura had submitted as required on his 75th birthday. Such resignations are either accepted by Pope Francis quickly, as in Ventura\u2019s case, or sometimes he kept bishops in their jobs longer.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-pope-france-envoy-idUKKBN1YL1CU|title=Vatican ambassador to France resigns after molestation allegations|last=|first=|date=2019-12-17|work=[[Reuters]]|access-date=2019-12-17|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20191217201207/https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-pope-france-envoy/vatican-ambassador-to-france-resigns-after-molestation-allegations-idUKKBN1YL1CU|archive-date=17 December 2019|language=en}}</ref> The fact that Ventura resignation was announced on the same day as Francis\u2019 abuse reforms does not seem to be a coincidence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ktvu.com/news/pope-francis-abolishes-pontifical-secret-in-clergy-sex-abuse-cases|title=Pope Francis abolishes 'pontifical secret' in clergy sex abuse cases|last=Winfield|first=Nicole|date=2019-12-17|website=FOX 29 [[KTVU]], [[Associated Press]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20191217224001/https://www.ktvu.com/news/pope-francis-abolishes-pontifical-secret-in-clergy-sex-abuse-cases|archive-date=17 December 2019|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref> The resignation and its acceptance had been anticipated since Ventura had been relieved of his responsibilities and moved to Rome in September. ''Lib\u00e9ration'', which published some of the earliest complaints against Ventura, called the idea of retiring without referencing the criminal charges against Ventura \"a beautiful example of Jesuitry\".<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.liberation.fr/france/2019/12/17/le-nonce-ventura-demisionne-pour-limite-d-age_1769824 | language = fr | title= Le nonce Ventura d\u00e9misionne\u2026 \u00abpour limite d\u2019\u00e2ge\u00bb | date= 17 December 2019 | access-date = 18 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{start box}}\n{{s-rel|ca}}\n{{succession box |\n    title=[[Apostolic Nuncio to Chile]] |\n    before=[[Piero Biggio]] |\n    after=[[Aldo Cavalli]] |\n    years=25 March 1999 \u2013 22 June 2001 }}\n\n{{succession box |\n    title=[[Apostolic Nunciature in Ottawa|Apostolic Nuncio to Canada]] |\n    before=[[Paolo Romeo]] |\n    after=[[Pedro Lopez Quintana]] |\n    years=22 June 2001 \u2013 22 September 2009 }}\n\n{{succession box |\n    title=[[Apostolic Nuncio to France]] |\n    before=[[Fortunato Baldelli]] |\n    after=[[Celestino Migliore]] |\n    years=22 September 2009 \u2013 17 December 2019 }}\n\n{{end box}}\n{{Roman Catholic dioceses in France|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Subject bar |portal1= Biography |portal2= Catholicism |portal3= France}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ventura, Luigi}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Apostolic Nuncios to France]]\n[[Category:Apostolic Nuncios to Canada]]\n[[Category:Apostolic Nuncios to Chile]]\n[[Category:Apostolic Nuncios to Ivory Coast]]\n[[Category:Apostolic Nuncios to Burkina Faso]]\n[[Category:Apostolic Nuncios to Niger]]\n[[Category:Italian titular archbishops]]\n[[Category:Pontifical Ecclesiastical Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:21st-century Roman Catholics]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type             = archbishop\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name             = Luigi Ventura \n| honorific-suffix = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| title            = Apostolic Nuncio emeritus to France\n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| church           = \n| archdiocese      = \n| province         = \n| metropolis       = \n| diocese          = \n| see              = \n| elected          = \n| appointed        = 22 September 2009\n| term             = \n| term_start       = \n| quashed          = \n| term_end         = 17 December 2019\n| predecessor      = [[Fortunato Baldelli]]\n| opposed          = \n| successor        = \n| other_post       = Titular Archbishop of Equilium\n<!---------- Orders ---------->\n| ordination       = 14 June 1969\n| ordained_by      = \n| consecration     = 29 April 1995\n| consecrated_by   = [[Angelo Sodano]]\n| cardinal         = \n| rank             = \n<!---------- Personal details ---------->\n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1944|12|09|df=yes}}\n| birth_place      = [[Borgosatollo]], Italy\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| buried           = \n| nationality      = \n| religion         = [[Roman Catholic]]\n| residence        = \n| parents          = \n| spouse           = \n| children         = \n| occupation       = \n| profession       = \n| previous_post    = {{unbulleted list|Apostolic Nuncio to Burkina Faso, Ivory Coast, and Niger (1995\u201399)|Apostolic Nuncio to Chile (1999\u20132001)|Apostolic Nuncio to Canada (2001\u201305)}}\n| education        =\n| alma_mater       = \n| motto            = Unitatem Spiritus Servare\n| signature        = \n| signature_alt    = \n| coat_of_arms     = Coat of arms of Luigi Ventura.svg\n| coat_of_arms_alt = \n<!---------- Other ---------->\n| other            = \n}}\n{{infobox bishopstyles |\n    name=Luigi Ventura|\n    dipstyle=[[The Most Reverend]] |\n    offstyle=[[Your Excellency]] |\n    relstyle=[[Archbishop]] |\n    deathstyle= |\n    image=Coat of arms of Luigi Ventura.svg|\n    image_size =200px|}}\n'''Luigi Ventura''' (born 9 December 1944) is an Italian prelate of the Catholic Church who was apostolic nuncio to France from 2009 to 2018. He became a nuncio and archbishop in 1995 and served in several African countries, Chile, and Canada before being posted to Paris.\n\nBeginning in January 2019 he was under investigation by French authorities for sexual crimes. In July 2019, the Vatican lifted his diplomatic immunity to allow him to face criminal charges. He was allowed to relocate to Rome; Pope Francis accepted his resignation in December 2019. The investigation remains open.\n\n==Career==\nVentura was born on 9 December 1944 in [[Borgosatollo]], Italy. He was ordained a priest on 14 June 1969 for the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Brescia|Diocese of Brescia]]. To prepare for a diplomatic career he entered the [[Pontifical Ecclesiastical Academy]] in 1967.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Pontifical Ecclesiastical Academy]]|language =it|access-date = 18 December 2019 | title = Pontificia Accademia Ecclesiastica, Ex-alunni 1950 \u2013 1999 |url = https://www.vatican.va/roman_curia/pontifical_academies/acdeccles/documents/1950-1999.htm }}</ref>\n\nHe joined the diplomatic service of the [[Holy See]] in 1978. He earned a doctor of letters and holds a [[Licentiate (degree)|licentiate]] in [[canon law]]. His assignments from 1978 to 1984 were in [[Brazil]], [[Bolivia]] and the [[United Kingdom]]. He then worked in Rome with the Section for Relations with States at the [[Secretariat of State (Holy See)|Secretariat of State]] until 1995.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/accused-nuncio-to-france-resigns-post-25730 | publisher = Catholic News Agency | access-date = 18 December 2019 | date= 17 December 2019 | title= Accused nuncio to France resigns post | first = Hannah | last = Brockhaus}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March 1995, [[Pope John Paul II]] appointed him [[titular archbishop]] of Equilium and apostolic nuncio to the [[Ivory Coast]], [[Burkina Faso]] and [[Niger]].<ref>{{cite book | page= 397 |access-date = 18 December 2019 | url = https://www.vatican.va/archive/aas/documents/AAS-87-1995-ocr.pdf |title = Acta Apostolicae Sedis | date= 1995| volume = LXXXVII }}</ref> He was consecrated a bishop on 29 April 1995 by Cardinal [[Angelo Sodano]], Secretary of State.{{cn|date=December 2019}} He was made nuncio to [[Chile]] on 25 March 1999.<ref>{{cite book | page= 479 |access-date = 18 December 2019 | url = https://www.vatican.va/archive/aas/documents/AAS-91-1999-ocr.pdf |title = Acta Apostolicae Sedis | date= 1999 | volume = LXXXXI }}</ref>\n\nOn 22 June 2001, John Paul named him apostolic nuncio to [[Canada]].<ref>{{cite news |access-date = 29 May 2019 | archive-date= 27 May 2014 | archive-url = https://archive.is/20140527173152/http://www.nationalpost.com/opinion/columnists/story.html?id=729cfb88-30f8-4171-9ace-7a2cf60ffbf4 |work= National Post |title=The Vatican's man in Canada|url = http://www.nationalpost.com/opinion/columnists/story.html?id=729cfb88-30f8-4171-9ace-7a2cf60ffbf4| url-status =dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite press release | title = Rinunce e Nomine, 22.06.2001| date= 22 June 2001 | language =it|url = http://press.vatican.va/content/salastampa/it/bollettino/pubblico/2001/06/22/0359/01058.html | publisher = Holy See Press Office}}</ref>\n\n[[Pope Benedict XVI]] appointed him apostolic nuncio to [[France]] on 22 September 2009,<ref>{{cite press release | title = Rinunce e Nomine, 22.09.2009 | date= 22 September 2009 | language =it|url =  http://press.vatican.va/content/salastampa/it/bollettino/pubblico/2009/09/22/0575/01336.html | publisher = Holy See Press Office}}</ref> replacing [[Fortunato Baldelli]] who had been appointed as [[Apostolic Penitentiary|Major Penitentiary of the Apostolic Penitentiary]].\n\n== Criminal allegations ==\n\nIn January 2019 the French authorities opened an investigation into Ventura after a junior official at Paris City Hall accused him of [[molestation]]. Ventura has not made comment on the allegations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.i24news.tv/en/news/international/europe/1576594182-pope-francis-lifts-pontifical-secret-for-sex-abuse-cases|title=Pope Francis lifts 'pontifical secret' for sex abuse cases|last=|first=|date=2019-12-17|website=[[i24NEWS]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213214944/https://www.i24news.tv/en/news/international/europe/1576594182-pope-francis-lifts-pontifical-secret-for-sex-abuse-cases|archive-date=13 February 2020|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 February 2019, ''[[Le Monde]]'' reported that a young male employed by the office of the mayor of Paris had filed a complaint for [[sexual assault]] against Ventura and that authorities had launched a formal inquiry in January.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.lemonde.fr/societe/article/2019/02/15/l-ambassadeur-du-pape-en-france-vise-par-une-enquete_5423780_3224.html | work = Le Monde | language = fr | title= L\u2019\" ambassadeur \" du pape en France, Luigi Ventura, vis\u00e9 par une enqu\u00eate pour \" agressions sexuelles \" | access-date = 29 May 2019 | date= 15 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | work = La Croix | access-date = 29 May 2019 | url = https://www.la-croix.com/Religion/Catholicisme/France/Le-nonce-apostolique-France-vise-enquete-agressions-sexuelles-2019-02-15-1201002817 | language = fr | date = 15 February 2019 | first = Gauthier | last = Vaillant|title= Le nonce apostolique en France vis\u00e9 par une enqu\u00eate pour agressions sexuelles }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.lejdd.fr/Societe/Justice/sopucons-dagression-sexuelle-le-cas-ventura-met-le-vatican-dans-lembarras-3859358 | language = fr | work = Journal de Dimanche | access-date = 29 May 2019 | title = Soup\u00e7ons d'agression sexuelle : le cas Ventura met le Vatican dans l'embarras| first = St\u00e9phane | last = Joahny | date= 17 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | access-date = 29 May 2019 | publisher = CNN | url = https://edition.cnn.com/2019/02/15/europe/vatican-france-envoy-luigi-ventura-investigation-intl/index.html | date= 15 February 2019 | title = Vatican envoy to France under investigation for sexual assault | first = Saskya | last = Vandoorne}}</ref> The city employee, Mathieu de La Souch\u00e8re, and two other accusers using aliases, have asked French officials to ask the Vatican to waive Ventura's [[diplomatic immunity]].<ref>{{cite news |work= La Lib\u00e9ration | url = https://www.liberation.fr/france/2019/02/28/emmanuel-macron-levez-l-immunite-diplomatique-du-nonce-apostolique_1711998 | access-date = 29 May 2019 | title = Emmanuel Macron, levez l'immunit\u00e9 diplomatique du nonce apostolique! | language = fr | date = 28 February 2019}}</ref> French European Minister [[Nathalie Loiseau]] said she expects the Vatican to allow Ventura to be tried.<ref>{{cite news | access-date = 29 May 2019 | date= 1 March 2019 | url = http://m.en.rfi.fr/europe/20190301-france-urges-vatican-action-papal-envoy-sex-abuse-luigi-ventura | publisher = RFI | title = France calls on Vatican to take action against envoy after sex abuse charges}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 February a Canadian man, Christian Vachon, charged Ventura had touched him improperly in July 2008 when he was 32.<ref>{{cite news| work = Pr\u00e9sence| language = fr | access-date =  30 May 2019 | date=26 February 2019 | url =http://presence-info.ca/article/judiciaire/premiere-plainte-d-inconduite-sexuelle-au-canada-contre-l-ancien-nonce | title = Premi\u00e8re plainte d\u2019inconduite sexuelle au Canada contre l\u2019ancien nonce | first =Philippe |last= Vaillancourt}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | access-date = 29 May 2019 | url = https://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/french-nuncio-accused-of-sexual-misconduct-during-time-in-canada-38730 | agency = Catholic News Agency | date= 1 March 2019 | title = French nuncio accused of sexual misconduct during time in Canada}}</ref> Vachon said Ventura's successor as Nuncio to Canada, Archbishop [[Luigi Bonazzi]], called him the day he registered his complaint to discuss it.<ref>{{cite news | access-date = 29 May 2019 | work = Crux | url = https://cruxnow.com/church-in-the-americas/2019/02/28/vatican-embassy-confirms-complaint-of-sexual-misconduct-against-ex-nuncio/ | title = Vatican embassy confirms complaint of sexual misconduct against ex-nuncio | first = Philippe | last = Vaillancourt |agency= Catholic News Service | date= 28 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nVentura allowed himself to be questioned by French police in April. At his own request, Ventura met with his four accusers on 22\u201323 May and denied their charges. The accusers' attorneys were not allowed to ask him questions.<ref name=confront>{{cite news | access-date = 29 May 2019 | url = https://www.la-croix.com/Religion/Catholicisme/France/Confronte-accusateurs-nonce-apostolique-nie-toute-agression-sexuelle-2019-05-23-1201024070 | title = Confront\u00e9 \u00e0 ses accusateurs, le nonce apostolique nie toute agression sexuelle |date= 23 May 2019| work = La Croix | first = Cl\u00e9mence | last = Houdaille | language = fr}}</ref> On 8 July a Vatican spokesperson said the [[Holy See]] had informed French authorities a week earlier that it was waiving Ventura's diplomatic immunity. He called it \"an extraordinary gesture\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/holy-see-waves-diplomatic-immunity-for-accused-nuncio-to-france-22125/|date= 8 July 2019 | title=Holy See waives diplomatic immunity for accused nuncio to France|website=Catholic News Agency|access-date=8 July 2019}}</ref> ''Le Monde'' reported it was the first withdrawal of diplomatic immunity on the part of the Vatican in modern history.<ref>{{cite news | access-date = 18 December 2019 | date= 17 December 2019 | language = fr | url = https://www.lemonde.fr/societe/article/2019/12/17/le-pape-francois-leve-le-secret-pontifical-sur-les-abus-sexuels-au-sein-de-l-eglise_6023182_3224.html | title= Le pape Fran\u00e7ois l\u00e8ve le secret pontifical sur les abus sexuels au sein de l\u2019Eglise catholique | first= C\u00e9cile | last = Chambraud }}</ref>\n\nAs of 30 September 2019, Ventura was living at a residence for retired priests in Rome,<ref>{{cite news | url = https://international.la-croix.com/news/papal-nuncio-to-france-accused-of-sexual-assault-back-in-rome/10933 | title= Papal nuncio to France accused of sexual assault back in Rome | date= 30 September 2019 | access-date = 17 December 2019 |newspaper=[[La Croix International]]}}</ref> still subject to French investigators and prosecution.<ref>{{cite news | access-date = 18 December 2019 | date= 17 December 2019 | work = The Tablet | title= Pope accepts France ambassador resignation| first = Christopher | last = Lamb| url = https://www.thetablet.co.uk/news/12298/pope-accepts-france-ambassador-resignation }}</ref>\n\n==Resignation==\nPope Francis accepted his resignation on 17 December 2019,<ref>{{cite press release | title = Resignations and Appointments, 17.12.2019  | date= 17 December 2019 | url = https://press.vatican.va/content/salastampa/en/bollettino/pubblico/2019/12/17/191217c.html  | publisher = Holy See Press Office}}</ref> which Ventura had submitted as required on his 75th birthday. Such resignations are either accepted by Pope Francis quickly, as in Ventura\u2019s case, or sometimes he kept bishops in their jobs longer.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-pope-france-envoy-idUKKBN1YL1CU|title=Vatican ambassador to France resigns after molestation allegations|last=|first=|date=2019-12-17|work=[[Reuters]]|access-date=2019-12-17|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20191217201207/https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-pope-france-envoy/vatican-ambassador-to-france-resigns-after-molestation-allegations-idUKKBN1YL1CU|archive-date=17 December 2019|language=en}}</ref> The fact that Ventura resignation was announced on the same day as Francis\u2019 abuse reforms does not seem to be a coincidence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ktvu.com/news/pope-francis-abolishes-pontifical-secret-in-clergy-sex-abuse-cases|title=Pope Francis abolishes 'pontifical secret' in clergy sex abuse cases|last=Winfield|first=Nicole|date=2019-12-17|website=FOX 29 [[KTVU]], [[Associated Press]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20191217224001/https://www.ktvu.com/news/pope-francis-abolishes-pontifical-secret-in-clergy-sex-abuse-cases|archive-date=17 December 2019|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref> The resignation and its acceptance had been anticipated since Ventura had been relieved of his responsibilities and moved to Rome in September. ''Lib\u00e9ration'', which published some of the earliest complaints against Ventura, called the idea of retiring without referencing the criminal charges against Ventura \"a beautiful example of Jesuitry\".<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.liberation.fr/france/2019/12/17/le-nonce-ventura-demisionne-pour-limite-d-age_1769824 | language = fr | title= Le nonce Ventura d\u00e9misionne\u2026 \u00abpour limite d\u2019\u00e2ge\u00bb | date= 17 December 2019 | access-date = 18 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{start box}}\n{{s-rel|ca}}\n{{succession box |\n    title=[[Apostolic Nuncio to Chile]] |\n    before=[[Piero Biggio]] |\n    after=[[Aldo Cavalli]] |\n    years=25 March 1999 \u2013 22 June 2001 }}\n\n{{succession box |\n    title=[[Apostolic Nunciature in Ottawa|Apostolic Nuncio to Canada]] |\n    before=[[Paolo Romeo]] |\n    after=[[Pedro Lopez Quintana]] |\n    years=22 June 2001 \u2013 22 September 2009 }}\n\n{{succession box |\n    title=[[Apostolic Nuncio to France]] |\n    before=[[Fortunato Baldelli]] |\n    after=[[incumbent]] |\n    years=22 September 2009 \u2013 17 December 2019 }}\n\n{{end box}}\n{{Roman Catholic dioceses in France|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Subject bar |portal1= Biography |portal2= Catholicism |portal3= France}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ventura, Luigi}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Apostolic Nuncios to France]]\n[[Category:Apostolic Nuncios to Canada]]\n[[Category:Apostolic Nuncios to Chile]]\n[[Category:Apostolic Nuncios to Ivory Coast]]\n[[Category:Apostolic Nuncios to Burkina Faso]]\n[[Category:Apostolic Nuncios to Niger]]\n[[Category:Italian titular archbishops]]\n[[Category:Pontifical Ecclesiastical Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:21st-century Roman Catholics]]\n", "name_user": "\u0e0a\u0e32\u0e27\u0e44\u0e17\u0e22", "label": "safe", "comment": "Already have a successor.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Luigi_Ventura"}
{"title_page": "Bombay Catholic Sabha", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\nThe '''[[Mumbai|Bombay]] Catholic Sabha (BCS)''' was founded on January 20, 1989 as a non-political organisation registered as a Public Trust, under the Bombay Public Trusts Act 1950. The BCS is a recognised lay association of the [[Archdiocese of Bombay]], affiliated to the [[All India Catholic Union]] (AICU) that is in turn recognised by the [[Catholic Bishops' Conference of India]]. It is one of the largest Christian organization in the country with a membership of over 60,000 with units and presence in four districts of Maharashtra. It represents Social issues including Human Rights, Civic and Political.\n\nIts registered office is at St. Michael\u2019s Church Annexe,L.J. Rd., Mahim (West), Mumbai 400016.\n\nThe Social Action Forum of the Sabha upholds social values of inter-religious harmony, protection of environment, senior citizens cards, etc .  It Enhances the knowledge on issues of mental and physical disabilities and addictions.  Conducts Health Camps for various needs of community members. Raises its voice against social injustice, community concerns, discrimination on basis of caste or creed etc.  Its conducts programs with the aim of encouraging the youth to answer competitive exams like Civil Services Exam etc\n\n\n\n. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bcsabha.org/index.html|title=Welcome to the official website of \" The Bombay Catholic Sabha \"|publisher=Bombay Catholic Sabha (BCS)|accessdate=2008-12-25}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Catholic Church in India]]\n[[Category:Catholic organizations established in the 20th century]]\n\n\n{{India-org-stub}}\n{{RC-society-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\nThe '''[[Mumbai|Bombay]] Catholic Sabha (BCS)''' was founded on January 20, 1989 as a non-political organisation registered as a Public Trust, under the Bombay Public Trusts Act 1950. The BCS is a recognised lay association of the [[Archdiocese of Bombay]], affiliated to the [[All India Catholic Union]] (AICU) that is in turn recognised by the [[Catholic Bishops' Conference of India]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bcsabha.org/index.html|title=Welcome to the official website of \" The Bombay Catholic Sabha \"|publisher=Bombay Catholic Sabha (BCS)|accessdate=2008-12-25}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Catholic Church in India]]\n[[Category:Catholic organizations established in the 20th century]]\n\n\n{{India-org-stub}}\n{{RC-society-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Alwyn2020", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bombay_Catholic_Sabha"}
{"title_page": "2020 United States presidential election in Florida", "text_new": "{{main|2020 United States presidential election}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name = 2020 [[United States presidential election]] in Florida\n| country = Florida\n| type = presidential\n| ongoing = no\n| previous_election = 2016 United States presidential election in Florida\n| previous_year     = 2016\n| election_date = November 3, 2020\n| next_election     = 2024 United States presidential election in Florida\n| next_year         = 2024\n| turnout = %\n| image_size = \n\n| image1 = Donald Trump official portrait (cropped).jpg\n| nominee1 = [[Donald Trump]]\n| party1 = Republican Party (United States)\n| home_state1 = [[Florida]]\n| running_mate1 = [[Mike Pence]]\n| electoral_vote1 =\n| popular_vote1 = \n| percentage1 = \n\n| image2 = Joe Biden 2013.jpg\n| nominee2 = [[Joe Biden]]\n| party2 = Democratic Party (United States)\n| home_state2 = [[Delaware]]\n| running_mate2 = TBA\n| electoral_vote2 =\n| popular_vote2 = \n| percentage2 = \n\n| title = President\n| before_election = [[Donald Trump]]\n| before_party = Republican Party (United States)\n| after_election = TBA\n| after_party = \n}}\n{{ElectionsFL}}\n\nThe '''2020 United States presidential election in Florida''' is scheduled to take place on Tuesday, November 3, 2020, as part of the [[2020 United States elections]] in which all 50 states plus the [[Washington, D.C.|District of Columbia]] will participate.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-elections-key-dates-midterms-2020-presidential-house-congress-senate-a8472821.html|title=US elections key dates: When are the 2018 midterms and the 2020 presidential campaign?|last=Kelly|first=Ben|date=August 13, 2018|work=[[The Independent]]|access-date=January 3, 2019}}</ref> [[Florida]] voters will choose electors to represent them in the [[United States Electoral College|Electoral College]] via a popular vote. The state of Florida has 29 electoral votes in the Electoral College.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.archives.gov/federal-register/electoral-college/allocation.html|title=Distribution of Electoral Votes|last=|first=|date=|website=[[National Archives and Records Administration]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=January 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Miami Beach, Florida]], which hosted the [[1972 Democratic National Convention]], was a finalist to host the [[2020 Democratic National Convention]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/community/miami-dade/miami-beach/article213670709.html|title=Cruise ship hotels, zoo parties and an NBA arena: Miami's Democratic convention pitch|work=miamiherald|access-date=July 1, 2018}}</ref> The other finalists were Milwaukee and Houston. Milwaukee was ultimately decided as the host.<ref name=\":0FL\">{{Cite news|url=https://fox6now.com/2018/06/20/city-of-milwaukee-named-as-1-of-3-finalists-to-host-2020-dnc-convention/|title=City of Milwaukee 1 of 3 finalists to host 2020 Democratic National Convention|date=2018-06-20|work=FOX6Now.com|access-date=2018-07-01|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.jsonline.com/story/news/politics/elections/2018/08/22/dnc-team-visiting-milwaukee-2020-democratic-convention-site/1065267002/|title=Selection committee for 2020 Democratic Convention will visit Milwaukee next week|last=Glauber|first=Bill|date=August 22, 2018|work=[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]|accessdate=August 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\nFlorida will also be incumbent president Donald Trump's home state for this election, after having identified New York as his home in 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/31/us/politics/trump-new-york-florida-primary-residence.html|title=Trump, Lifelong New Yorker, Declares Himself a Resident of Florida|last=Haberman|first=Maggie|date=November 4, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=}}</ref> As a result, Trump became the first nominee of either major party to be from Florida.\n\n==Primary elections==\nThe primary elections were held on March 17, 2020.\n\n===Republican primary===\nThe Florida secretary of state declared [[Rocky De La Fuente]] to be a major candidate and thus worthy of automatic inclusion on the ballot.\n \n{{excerpt|2020 Florida Republican primary|fragment=FLresults}}\n\n===Democratic primary===\nThree Democrats were still in race by the time Florida held its primaries: [[Vermont]] [[United States Senate|Senator]] [[Bernie Sanders]], former [[Vice President of the United States|vice president]] [[Joe Biden]], and [[United States House of Representatives|Representative]] from [[Hawaii]] [[Tulsi Gabbard]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Taylor |first1=Kate |title=Elizabeth Warren Formally Announces 2020 Presidential Bid in Lawrence, Mass. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/09/us/politics/elizabeth-warren-2020.html |accessdate=10 February 2019 |publisher=The New York Times |date=9 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Zhou |first1=Li |title=Kamala Harris announces her historic 2020 presidential campaign |url=https://www.vox.com/2019/1/21/18175628/kamala-harris-2020-campaign-president |accessdate=10 February 2019 |publisher=Vox |date=21 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Detrow |first1=Scott |title=Cory Booker Makes It Official: He's Running For President In 2020 |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/02/01/676578945/cory-booker-makes-it-official-hes-running-for-president-in-2020 |accessdate=10 February 2019 |publisher=NPR |date=1 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe first Democratic debate took place in [[Miami]] over two nights at the end of June 2019. It was broadcast on several of the [[NBC]] networks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/first-democratic-debate-2020-election|title=First Democratic Debate 2019: Highlights, candidates and more|website=NBC News}}</ref>\n\n{{excerpt|2020 Florida Democratic primary|fragment=FLresults}}\n\n==General election==\n===Predictions===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!Source\n!Ranking\n!As of\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[The Cook Political Report]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cookpolitical.com/sites/default/files/2020-03/EC%20030920.4.pdf|title=2020 POTUS Race ratings|website=The Cook Political Report|language=en|access-date=2019-05-21}}</ref>\n|{{USRaceRating|Tossup}}\n|March 9, 2020\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Stuart Rothenberg|Inside Elections]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://insideelections.com/ratings/president|title=POTUS Ratings {{!}} Inside Elections|website=insideelections.com|access-date=2019-05-21}}</ref>\n|{{USRaceRating|Tossup}}\n|April 3, 2020\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Sabato's Crystal Ball]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://centerforpolitics.org/crystalball/2020-president/|title=Larry J. Sabato's Crystal Ball \u00bb 2020 President|website=crystalball.centerforpolitics.org|access-date=2019-05-21}}</ref>\n|{{USRaceRating|Lean|R}}\n|April 2, 2020\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Politico]]<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://www.politico.com/2020-election/race-forecasts-and-predictions/president/ |title=2020 Election Forecast|date=November 19, 2019 |publisher=[[Politico]]}}</ref>\n|{{USRaceRating|Tossup}}\n|November 19, 2019\n|}\n\n===Polling===\n====Aggregate polls====\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+\n!colspan=\"7\"|Donald Trump vs. Joe Biden\n|-\n!Source of poll aggregation\n!Dates administered\n!Dates updated\n![[Joe Biden]]\n![[Donald Trump]]\n!Other/Undecided{{Efn|Calculated by taking the difference of 100% and all other candidates combined.|name=|group=}}\n!Margin\n|-\n|[https://www.270towin.com/2020-polls-biden-trump/florida/ 270 to Win]\n|March 16, 2020 - April 6, 2020\n|April 6, 2020\n|{{party shading/Democratic}}|'''45.5%'''\n|44.0%\n|\n|{{party shading/Democratic}}|{{hs|1.5}}'''Biden + 1.5'''\n|-\n|[https://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2020/president/fl/florida_trump_vs_biden-6841.html Real Clear Politics]\n|March 5, 2020 - April 4, 2020\n|April 4, 2020\n|{{party shading/Democratic}}|'''46.7%'''\n|46.3%\n|\n|{{party shading/Democratic}