th Warren\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%;text-align:center;\"\n|- valign=bottom style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n! Poll source\n! Date(s)<br>administered\n! Sample<br>size{{efn|name=key}}\n! Margin<br>{{nowrap|of error}}\n! Mike<br>Pence (R)\n! Elizabeth<br>Warren (D)\n! Other\n! Undecided\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [https://www.unf.edu/publicrelations/media_relations/press/2019/New_UNF_Poll_Reveals_Florida_Torn_Over_Trump_Impeachment_Inquiry.aspx University of North Florida]\n| Oct 14-20, 2019\n| 643 (RV)\n| \u00b1&nbsp;3.8%\n|40%\n|{{party shading/Democratic}}|'''46%'''\n|8%{{efn|Wouldn't vote with 8%}}\n|6%\n|}\n{{collapse bottom}}\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[2020 United States presidential election]]\n* [[2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries]]\n* [[2020 Republican Party presidential primaries]]\n* [[2020 United States elections]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n;Partisan clients\n{{notelist-ua}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{United States elections, 2020}}\n\n[[Category:2020 United States presidential election by state|Florida]]\n[[Category:United States presidential elections in Florida|2020]]\n[[Category:2020 Florida elections|Presidential]]\n", "name_user": "MyPreferredUsernameWasTaken", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRepublican primary", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_United_States_presidential_election_in_Florida"}
